SIMPLE: suck
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Suck
<hw>Suck</hw> <pr>(s⟦ucr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sucked</conjf> <pr>(s⟦ucr⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sucking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>suken</ets>,
<ets>souken</ets>, AS. <ets>s⟦umac⟧can</ets>, <ets>s⟦umac⟧gan</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>zuigen</ets>, G. <ets>saugen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>s⟦umac⟧gan</ets>, Icel. <ets>s⟦umac⟧ga</ets>,
<ets>sj⟦umac⟧ga</ets>, Sw. <ets>suga</ets>, Dan. <ets>suge</ets>, L.
<ets>sugere</ets>. Cf. <er>Honeysuckle</er>, <er>Soak</er>,
<er>Succulent</er>, <er>Suction</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw,
as a liquid, by the action of the mouth and tongue, which tends to
produce a vacuum, and causes the liquid to rush in by atmospheric
pressure; to draw, or apply force to, by exhausting the air.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw liquid from by the action of the mouth;
<as>as, to <ex>suck</ex> an orange</as>; specifically, to draw milk from
(the mother, the breast, etc.) with the mouth; <as>as, the young of an
animal <ex>sucks</ex> the mother, or dam; an infant <ex>sucks</ex> the
breast</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To draw in, or imbibe, by any process resembles
sucking; to inhale; to absorb; <as>as, to <ex>suck</ex> in air; the
roots of plants <ex>suck</ex> water from the ground</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To draw or drain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Old ocean, <qex>sucked</qex> through the porous globe.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To draw in, as a whirlpool; to swallow up.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As waters are by whirlpools <qex>sucked</qex> and drawn.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To suck in</b></col>, <cd>to draw into the mouth; to
imbibe; to absorb.</cd> -- <col><b>To suck out</b></col>, <cd>to draw
out with the mouth; to empty by suction.</cd> -- <col><b>To suck
up</b></col>, <cd>to draw into the mouth; to draw up by suction or
absorption.</cd></cs> <-- suck up (b) to be obsequious; to act as a
toady. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Suck
<hw>Suck</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw, or attempt to
draw, something by suction, as with the mouth, or through a
tube.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where the bee <qex>sucks</qex>, there <qex>suck</qex> I.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw milk from the breast or udder; <as>as, a
child, or the young of an animal, is first nourished by
<ex>sucking</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To draw in; to imbibe; to partake.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The crown had <qex>sucked</qex> too hard, and now, being full, was
like to draw less.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be objectionable, of very poor quality, or
offensive; <as>as, telemarketing calls really <ex>suck</ex>; he's a good
actor, but his singing <ex>sucks</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Suck
<hw>Suck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of drawing with
the mouth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is drawn into the mouth by sucking;
specifically, mikl drawn from the breast.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A small draught.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
<rj><au>Massinger.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Juice; succulence.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suckanhock</ent>⟦br⟧
